<HEADLINE>
THREE MORE TAIWAN COMPANIES BECOME WEF MEMBERS
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Geneva,  Jan. 16 (CNA) 01/17/07  11:51:32 (By Neil Lu and Deborah
Kuo)
</P>
<P>
Three more Taiwan companies have recently become formal members
of the World Economic Forum (WEF) ,  a Geneva-based independent
international organization committed to improving the state of
the world.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan's High Tech Computer (HTC), Chunghwa Telecom, and Chinese
Petroleum Corp. (CPC) have recently been admitted as members of
the forum, which provides a collaborative framework for the
world's leaders to address global issues, engaging particularly
its corporate members in global citizenship.
</P>
<P>
HTC, CPC and Chunghwa Telecom's joining the WEF is expected to
boost interactions and exchanges between Taiwan and the WEF.
</P>
<P>
The forum is open to multinational corporations that are listed
as the world's top 1,000 companies to apply for membership.
</P>
<P>
WEF authorities  has recently  offered 25 Taiwan companies
opportunities to become WEF members. Although CPC was not ranked
among the world's top 1,000 companies in 2006 due to decreased
revenues, it was admitted as a WEF member as a "special" case,
according to the WEF authorities.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan's VIA Technologies Inc. and the Uni-President Group were
admitted to the WEF several years ago. VIA is a sister company of
HTC.
</P>
<P>
HTC Chairwomen Cher Wang, HTC President Chen Wen-chi and Chunghwa
Telecom President Lu Hsueh-chin are scheduled to take part in the
WEF 2007 annual meeting set to be held in Davos, Switzerland Jan.
24-28.
</P>
